ority of mothers, drawing upon emerging scientific and cultural ideas about maternal instinct, infant development, and connections between the body and mind, pushed back against both hospital policies and cultural norms by breastfeeding their children. As Martucci shows, their choices helped ideologically root a “back to the breast” movement within segments of the middle-class, college-educated population as early as the 1950s. That movement—in which the personal and political were inextricably linked—effectively challenged midcentury norms of sexuality, gender, and consumption, and articulated early environmental concerns about chemical and nuclear contamination of foods, bodies, and breast milk. In its groundbreaking chronicle of the breastfeeding movement, Back to the Breast provides a welcome and vital account of what it has meant, and what it means today, to breastfeed in modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBreastfeeding promotionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBreastfeedingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aInfantsxNutritionzUnited States. 0aMaternal and infant welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotherhoodzUnited States. 0aMotherszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy20th century. 70(DE-601)1061504990(DE-588)4057578-0aStillen2gnd 70(DE-601)1061779230(DE-588)4051255-1aSäugling2gnd 70(DE-601)10626737X0(DE-588)4031081-4aKleinkind2gnd 70(DE-601)1063370920(DE-588)4015332-0aErnährung2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  amotherhood, mother, parent, parenthood, gender, breastfeeding, united states of america, american culture, usa, natural, nature, medical ethics, ethical, morality, morals, medicine, health policy, naturalism movement, maternal instincts, infant development, children, child, kid, political, sexuality, consumption, breast mi